---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import CronGeneratorIsland from '../../islands/CronGeneratorIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('cron-generator')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <CronGeneratorIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Use the visual builder to set the minute, hour, day-of-month, month, and day-of-week
        fields, and the cron expression is generated in real time. Alternatively, type a cron
        expression directly into the input field and the tool will explain each field in plain
        English and show the next five scheduled run times.
      </p>
      <p>
        Cron is used extensively for scheduling recurring tasks: database backups, report
        generation, cache invalidation, sending scheduled emails, rotating log files, and
        triggering CI/CD pipelines on a schedule. This tool also supports the non-standard
        <code>@reboot</code>, <code>@daily</code>, <code>@weekly</code>, and
        <code>@monthly</code> shorthand strings used by many cron implementations.
      </p>
      <p>
        The expression preview and next-run calculator run entirely in your browser — useful
        for verifying a schedule before deploying it to production.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What does */5 mean in a cron expression?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          The <code>*/5</code> syntax means "every 5 units." In the minute field,
          <code>*/5</code> runs the job at minutes 0, 5, 10, 15 … 55 — effectively every 5
          minutes. In the hour field it would run every 5 hours. The <code>*</code> stands for
          "every possible value" and dividing by the step selects evenly spaced values.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I schedule a cron job to run every hour?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Use <code>0 * * * *</code> to run at the top of every hour, or the shorthand
          <code>@hourly</code>. If you want it to run at a specific minute past the hour — for
          example 15 minutes past — use <code>15 * * * *</code>.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the format of a standard cron expression?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          A standard cron expression has five space-separated fields:
          <code>minute hour day-of-month month day-of-week</code>. Each field accepts a number,
          a wildcard (<code>*</code>), a range (<code>1-5</code>), a list
          (<code>1,3,5</code>), or a step value (<code>*/2</code>). Some systems add a sixth
          field for seconds at the beginning.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I run a job on weekdays only?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Set the day-of-week field to <code>1-5</code>, where 1 is Monday and 5 is Friday.
          For example, <code>0 9 * * 1-5</code> runs the job every weekday at 09:00.
          Note that Sunday can be represented as either 0 or 7 depending on the cron
          implementation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
